<subsection xml:id="subsec-number-sequence">
    <title>Number sequence</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            A number sequence is a list of numbers that follow a specific pattern or rule. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Think of it like a list of numbers where each number is related to the one before it in a certain way e.g <m>2, 4, 6, 8, 10, ...</m>
            Here, you are adding 2 each time. These are all numbers that can be divided by 2.
        </p> 
        <p>
            The pattern could involve adding, subtracting, multiplying, or dividing by a certain number each time.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-identifying-a-number-sequence">
        <title>Identifying a number sequence</title>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{How to recognize a number sequence}</m>   
        </p>
        <p>
            Look for the pattern. Identify if the numbers are increasing or decreasing. Find out if there is consistent amount being added or subtracted.
        </p>
        <p>
            See if you can predict the next number based on the rule you find.
        </p>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                  1. Working in groups of <m>5</m>, each group to write down the following sequence:    
                </p>
                <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Sequence: <m>3\, ,6\,, 9\, ,12\,</m>,___
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Sequence: <m> 4\, ,8\, ,16\, ,32\, </m>,___ 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Sequence: <m> 1\, ,4\, , 9\, ,16\,</m>, ____
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Sequence: <m> 1\, ,1\, ,2\,, 3\, ,5\, ,8\,</m>, ___
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    2. Each team to take <m>3</m> minutes to solve each question and work together to identify the pattern and fill in the missing number.
                </p>
                <p>
                    3. At the end of 3 minutes, each group will present their answer to the class.
                </p>
                <p>
                    4. The group should explain the pattern they identified that is why it works and how they figured it out.
                </p>
                <p>
                    5. Discuss where you see number patterns in nature, technology, and everyday life.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Identify the missing number in the following sequences. 
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>50\, ,400\,, 850\, ,1400\,</m>,___,___,___ 
            </p>
        </statement>
           <solution>
            <p>
               1. The first step is to find the differences between consecutive numbers:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>400 - 50 = 350 </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>850 - 400 = 450</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1400 - 850 = 550</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                So, the differences are <m>350\, ,450\,, 550\,</m> which are increasing by <m>100</m> each time.
            </p>
            <p>
                 2. Next step is to predict the next differences:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m> 550 + 100 = 650</m> (the next difference)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>650 + 100 = 750</m> (the following difference)
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m> 750 + 100 = 850 </m>(the last difference)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                3.Add these differences to the last known number (1400):
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>1400 + 650 = 2050 </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2050 + 750 = 2800</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2800 + 850 = 3650</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                So the missing numbers are <m>2050 \,,2800\,,3650 </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                4. Finally, the sequence is <m>50\, ,400\,, 850\, ,1400\, ,2050\, ,2800\, ,3650</m>
            </p>
            </solution>
        </example> 
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Rearrange the following numbers in ascending order and identify the next two numbers in each sequence.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>648\, ,24\, ,216\,,8\,,72</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                  The given numbers are: <m>648\,, 24\, ,216\, ,8\, ,72</m> . 
                </p>
                <p>
                    When rearranged in ascending order, we get:
                </p>
                <p>
                   <m>8\, ,24\,, 72\, ,216\,, 648</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Now, let's examine the relationship between the numbers:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m> 8 \times 3 = 24</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>24 \times 3 = 72</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                              <m> 72 \times 3 = 216</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m> 216 \times 3 = 648</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    From the above,each number is being multiplied by 3 to get the next number.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the next <m>2</m> numbers are:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m> 648 \times 3 = 1944</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1944 \times 3 = 5832</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The missing numbers are <m>1944,5832</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>   
    </subsubsection>   
<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-creating-a-number-sequence">
    <title>Creating a number sequence</title>
    <p>
        To create a number sequence, you need the first number in the sequence and the rule connecting the next numbers.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
               There are 6 students in the class, and each student adds 2 books to a table.
               The 1st student places <m>2</m> books, the 2nd student places another <m>2</m>, and so on.
            </p>
            <p>
               1. Record the total number of books as each student adds books on the table after each turn.
            </p>
            <p>
               2. Figure out the sequence of books on the table and explore how patterns form. 
            </p>
            <p>
                3.Create different sequences using the same setup by changing the rules for adding books and generate new sequences i.e
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Add an increasing number of books each time - this is a sequence where the 2nd student add 2, then third student 3, then forth student 4, and so on.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each student can multiply the number of books added by the previous student like if previous student places <m>2</m> books the nextm will place <m>4</m> then the next will place<m>8</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Each group to share their sequences with the class and explain the rule or pattern they used to generate their sequence .
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Create a number sequence that starts at 60,000 upto the fifth term and follows the rule of dividing by 5. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since we have the 1st term and a rule, we can calculate the subsequent terms.
            </p>
            <p><ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       First term: <m>60\,000 </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Second term: <m>60,000 รท 5 = 12\,000</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Third term: <m>12,000 รท 5 = 2\,400</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Fourth term: <m>2,400 รท 5 = 480</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Fifth term: <m>480 รท 5 = 96</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The final sequence is: <m>60\,000\, ,12\,000\, ,2\,400\, ,480\, ,96</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Morara is a businessman. Every day, he deposits sh <m>1,250</m> into his bank account.
                Create a pattern to show his bank account balance at the end of each day for one week.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Assume Morara starts with 0 shillings in his account at the beginning.
            </p>
            <p>
                A week has <m>7</m> days and his account balance on the first day is sh <m>1,250</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 1: <m>0 + 1250 = 1250</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 2: <m>1250 + 1250 = 2500</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 3: <m>2500 + 1250 = 3750</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 4: <m>3750 + 1250 = 5000</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 5: <m>5000 + 1250 = 6250</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 6: <m>6250 + 1250 = 7500</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Day 7: <m>7500 + 1250 = 8750</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
               </ul> 
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the sequence of Morara's bank account balance at the end of each day for one week is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>1250\, ,2500\, ,3750\, ,5000\,, 6250\, ,7500\, ,8750</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
